'''Teboho Mokoena'''<ref name=SW/> (born 24 January 1997) is a South African professional [[association football|soccer player]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[South African Premiership|Premiership]] side [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] and the [[South Africa national soccer team|South Africa national team]].

==Club career==
During his schooling, Mokoena was discovered by Charles Molefe, a teacher doubling up as a soccer coach at Bodikela Junior Secondary School. His performances at school level earned him a sport at the Harmony Sports Academy from where he was picked up by [[SuperSport United F.C.|SuperSport United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/psl/my-mom-is-extremely-proud-says-supersports-teboho-mokoena-9953589|title=My mom is extremely proud, says SuperSport's Teboho Mokoena|publisher=Independent Online|last=Molefe|first=Mazola|date=24 June 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> At SuperSport United, he progressed through the academy and later captained the club at U-19 level.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/high-drama-in-metropolitan-cup-high-drama-in-metropolitan-cup-high-drama-in-metropolitan-u19-premier-cup-high-drama-in-metropolitan-cup-20160328|title=High drama in Metropolitan Cup|publisher=News 24|date=29 March 2016|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> He was promoted to the first-team in 2016 by [[Stuart Baxter]] and made his professional debut in February the following year, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Cole Alexander]] in a 5–2 league win over [[Golden Arrows F.C.|Golden Arrows]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/68533/supersport-united-promote-teboho-mokoena|title=SuperSport United promote Teboho Mokoena|publisher=Kick Off|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=SL>{{cite news|url=https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/articles/local/categories/bafana/teboho-mokoena-is-on-his-way-to-the-u20-world-cup/267157|title=SuperSport Starlet On His Way To World Cup|publisher=Soccer Laduma|last=Crann|first=Joe|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sundayworld/sport/2018-03-18-bafana-star-teboho-mokoena-still-respects-the-curfew/|title=Bafana star Teboho Mokoena still respects the curfew|publisher=Sowetan Live|last=Motswhane|first=Gomolemo|date=18 March 2018|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> In March 2017, after having become a regular feature in SuperSport United's midfield alongside [[Dean Furman]] and [[Reneilwe Letsholonyane]], Mokoena was at the centre of a club-versus-country row when Baxter refused to release him for international duty for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] due his commitment to the club's impending [[Nedbank Cup]] semi-final match. A compromise was ultimately reached between the two parties, which resulted in Mokoena being specially flown up to join his international teammates after SuperSport United confirmed their progression in the tournament.<ref name=SL/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.kickoff.com/news/75144/stuart-baxter-impressed-with-teboho-mokoena-for-taking-his-chances-in-supersport-united-first-team|title=Stuart Baxter impressed with Teboho Mokoena for taking his chances in SuperSport United first-team|publisher=Kick Off|last=Madlala|first=Robin-Duke|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> He returned in time for the final but was an unused substitute as the club beat [[Orlando Pirates F.C.|Orlando Pirates]] 4–1 to claim the title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kickoff.com/match-report/13461/match-report-nedbank-cup-orlando-pirates-vs-supersport-united|title=Match report – Nedbank Cup: SuperSport United vs Orlando Pirates|publisher=Kick Off|date=24 June 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> Before the final, he had also scored his first professional goal in a 2–2 [[CAF Confederations Cup]] draw with [[TP Mazembe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/articles/categories/caff-confederation-cup/caf-confederation-cup-report-tp-mazembe-supersport-united-04-june-2017/269929?page=6|title=SuperSport Comeback To Snatch A Point At Champions Mazembe|publisher=Soccer Laduma|date=4 June 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>

The following season, Mokoena continued to feature regularly for SuperSport United. He managed two goals and two assists for the season, and, despite the club finishing a disappointing eighth in the league, he was nominated for the [[PSL Awards|PSL Young Player of the Season]] award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/86339/analysing-psl-young-player-season-nomine|title=Analysing PSL Young Player of the Season nominees Sibusiso Mabaliso, Teboho Mokoena and Siphesihle Ndlovu|publisher=Kick Off|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=10 February 2019|last=De Dominicis|first=Fabio}}</ref> On 13 March 2019, he was awarded the league's Goal of the Month award for January following his strike against [[Bloemfontein Celtic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.supersport.com/football/absa-premiership/news/190313_Mokoena_wins_Absa_Prem_goal_of_the_month_for_January|title=Mokoena wins Absa Prem goal of the month for January|publisher=SuperSport|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>

==International career==
In July 2017, Mokoena received his first call-up to the [[South Africa national football team|senior national team]] by former SuperSport United manager Stuart Baxter, who had departed the club at the end of the [[2016–17 South African Premiership|2016–17]] domestic season, for the nation's [[2018 African Nations Championship]] [[2018 African Nations Championship qualification|qualifiers]]. He made his debut on 15 July against [[Botswana national football team|Botswana]] and was praised following the match for his ability to "carry the team on his shoulders".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-07-21-00-mokoena-easily-carries-bafana|title=Mokoena easily carries Bafana|publisher=Mail & Guardian|last=Kwenaite|first=Thomas|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> The following year, he scored his first international goal in South Africa's [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] win over [[Seychelles national football team|Seychelles]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/90160/supersport-united-coach-kaitano-tembo-ho|title=SuperSport United coach Kaitano Tembo is hoping Teboho Mokoena can feature more for Bafana Bafana|publisher=Kick Off|date=23 October 2018|accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> His goal also contributed towards the nation recording its largest ever victory with the match ending 6–0 in favour of South Africa.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/bafana/bafana-bafana-rock-seychelles-in-record-victory-17465043|title=Bafana Bafana rock Seychelles in record victory|publisher=Independent Online|last=Molefe|first=Mazola|date=13 October 2018|accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref>

Mokoena was later involved in a major scandal when he failed to serve one-match suspension in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] home match against [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]], which resulted in South Africa being handed a 3–0 walkover loss (having won 2–0 earlier).<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-09-29 |title=World Cup 2026 qualifying: South Africa handed forfeit for ineligible player |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cvgq08g64e6o |access-date=2026-05-26 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Nonetheless, thanked to favourable results earlier, South Africa were able to rebound and qualify for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

On 1 December 2025, Mokoena was called up to the South Africa squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/totalenergies-afcon-morocco-2025-fever-rises-as-broos-become-first-coach-to-unveil-final-squad/|title=TotalEnergies AFCON Morocco 2025 fever rises as Broos become first coach to unveil final squad|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=1 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

